We have to count the number of ordered triples $(a, b, c)$ of positive integers such that the decimal representations of $a, b, c$ contain 4 ones and 3 threes among them and no other digits. Let $f(n, k)$ be the number of $n$-digit numbers using only ones and threes that have $k$ ones. Then the number of ordered triples is
\[\sum_{i+j+k=7} f(4, i)f(3, j)f(3, k).\]We have $f(n, k) = f(n-1, k) + f(n-1, k-1)$, so we can build the following table:
\begin{tabular}{c|cccc}   & $f(n,0)$ & $f(n,1)$ & $f(n,2)$ & $f(n,3)$ \\ \hline f(n-1,0) & 1        & 1        & 1        & 1        \\ f(n-1,1) & 1        & 2        & 3        & 4        \\ f(n-1,2) & 1        & 3        & 6        & 10       \\ f(n-1,3) & 1        & 4        & 10       & 20       \end{tabular}
Then we get
\begin{align*} \sum_{i+j+k=7} f(4, i)f(3, j)f(3, k) &= \sum_{i+j+k=7} f(4, i) \cdot \binom{3}{j} \cdot \binom{3-j}{k} \\ &= \sum_{i=0}^4 f(4, i) \cdot \binom{3}{7-i} \cdot \binom{3}{4-i} \\ &= f(4, 1) \cdot \binom{3}{6} \cdot \binom{2}{3} + f(4, 2) \cdot \binom{3}{5} \cdot \binom{1}{2} + f(4, 3) \cdot \binom{3}{4} \cdot \binom{0}{1} \\ &= (2+3+4) \cdot 3 \cdot 1 + (3+6+4) \cdot 3 \cdot 2 + (4+10+4) \cdot 3 \cdot 1 \\ &= \boxed{129}. \end{align*}

