Solution:
There are ${7 \choose 2} = 21$ ways to choose two vertices of the heptagon.  Any two vertices determine one of the heptagon's diagonals.  Thus, there are ${7 \choose 2} = 21$ diagonals in the heptagon.  So, there are ${21 \choose 2} = 210$ ways to choose two diagonals without regard to order.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

int i;

draw(Circle((0,0),1));
for (i = 0; i <= 6; ++i) {
  dot(dir(360*i/7));
  draw(dir(360*i/7)--dir(360*(i + 1)/7));
}

draw(dir(360*0/7)--dir(360*3/7),red);
draw(dir(360*1/7)--dir(360*6/7),red);

label("$A$", dir(360*0/7), dir(360*0/7));
label("$B$", dir(360*1/7), dir(360*1/7));
label("$C$", dir(360*2/7), dir(360*2/7));
label("$D$", dir(360*3/7), dir(360*3/7));
label("$E$", dir(360*4/7), dir(360*4/7));
label("$F$", dir(360*5/7), dir(360*5/7));
label("$G$", dir(360*6/7), dir(360*6/7));

label("$X$", dir(360*0/7) + dir(360*3/7)/2, red);
label("$Y$", dir(360*1/7) + dir(360*6/7)/2, red);
[/asy]

We now count the number of ways to choose two diagonals that intersect inside the heptagon.  Choose one diagonal $DX,$ as shown above.  The other diagonal $EY$ must intersect $DX$ inside the heptagon.  Therefore, $E$ and $Y$ must lie on opposite sides of line $DX.$  There are two choices for $E,$ and once $E$ has been chosen, there is exactly one choice for $Y.$  Therefore, there are $2 \cdot 7 = 14$ pairs of diagonals that intersect inside the heptagon.

The probability that two randomly chosen diagonals intersect inside the heptagon is $\dfrac{14}{210} = \boxed{\frac{2}{15}}.$
